'''Karusato Ōtsuka Kofun''' (軽里大塚古墳) is a {{ill|Kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Habikino, Osaka|ja|羽曳野市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Osaka Prefecture. The tumulus is keyhole-shaped and is one of the tumuli that type the {{ill|Furuichi Kofun Group|ja|古市古墳群|12=draft|12=draft}}, a {{ill|UNESCO World Heritage Site|ja|世界文化遺産|12=draft|12=draft}}.

Although the actual person interred is unknown, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft|12=draft}} has Historic Site1 it as {{ill|Shiratori Ryo|ja|白鳥陵|12=draft|12=draft}}, the tomb of {{ill|Yamato Takeru|ja|日本武尊|1=Yamato Takeru|lt=Prince Yamato Takeru|3=ヤマトタケル|12=draft|12=draft}} (prince of {{ill|Emperor Keikō|ja|景行天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} and father of {{ill|Emperor Chūai|ja|仲哀天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}). Additionally, the surrounding moat has been Historic Site1 a National Historic Site as part of the Furuichi Kofun Group.<ref name=":kanpo">Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology Notification No. 48, March 26, 2021.</ref>

Also referred to as "Maenoyama Kofun" or "Shiratori Ryo Kofun," the tumulus is the namesake of {{ill|Habikino, Osaka|ja|羽曳野市|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==

Located in the southern part of the {{ill|Furuichi Kofun Group|ja|古市古墳群|12=draft|12=draft}}, the tumulus lies south of {{ill|Hakayama Kofun|ja|墓山古墳|1=Hakayama Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} and northeast of {{ill|Shiragiyama Kofun|ja|白髪山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}. The tumulus measures approximately 190 meters in length, with the back circular portion measuring about 106 meters in diameter and 20 meters in height. The front rectangular portion is approximately 165 meters wide and 23 meters high. The tumulus has three tiers, with the front portion oriented westward. A {{ill|Protrusion (kofun)|ja|造り出し|12=draft|12=draft}} is found in the northern constriction area, and the mound is surrounded by a 35-meter-wide moat and a 21-meter-wide embankment.

The primary burial chamber and grave goods are unknown. However, an excavation conducted in 1981 confirmed a {{ill|Haniwa|ja|埴輪|12=draft|12=draft}} row at the back portion of the mound, along with haniwa in types such as morning glory flowers, houses, and lids. Based on these finds and the tumulus type—where the width of the front rectangular portion is approximately 1.5 times the diameter of the back circular portion—the tumulus is estimated to have been built in the late 5th century, around the same time as {{ill|Ichinoyama Kofun|ja|市ノ山古墳|12=draft|12=draft}}, also part of the Furuichi Kofun Group.

In 2021, the surrounding moat was Historic Site1 a National Historic Site, as an additional part of the Furuichi Kofun Group.<ref name=":kanpo" />

